many swing voters skeptical. and if its details survive scrutiny, it is good for a country where bold, ground-breaking ideas get headlines but only pragmatically leavened proposals become law. ...(candidate last) has shown she understands not only the art of the possible but the value of the pragmatic. in tailoring her proposal to fit the needs and finesse the concerns of suburban voters, (candidate last) has decided the way to victory - in the election and eventually in congress - is down moderate main street." [newsday,9/19/07 ] </p><p><strong>google ceo eric schmidt on hillary - she 'was organized; she knew her stuff; she listened carefully; she responded to ideas':</strong> "for months, she has been meeting with business leaders one-on-one and in small groups to explore health-care issues. many have come away impressed, including eric schmidt, chief executive of google inc. "she was organized; she knew her stuff; she listened carefully; she responded to ideas," he said." [wall street journal, 9/20/07 ] </p><p><strong>national federation of independent businesses - 'one of the standout features of this is it specifically looks to help small business owners, and that's a good thing'</strong> [wall street journal, 9/20/07] </p><p><strong>washington post's steven pearlstein - hillary's plan 'beats anything else out there from candidates of either party':</strong> "her reform agenda isn't perfect, but it sure beats anything else out there from candidates of either party in terms of addressing all the important issues and coming up with a policy framework that is internally consistent and realistic in both a financial sense and a political one." [washington post, 9/19/07 ] </p><p><strong>m.i.t.'s jonathan gruber -- hillary's plan is 'excellent':</strong> "jonathan gruber, an economics professor at m.i.t. who helped create the lauded massachusetts health care system (and who advised all of the leading (PARTY NAME) on their health care plans), said he found the (candidate last) proposal to be 'excellent.' he said that it went further than the (candidate last) plan in that it mandated universal coverage, and was more progressive than the (candidate last) campaign's in that it would end tax breaks on health-care benefits for wealth americans that went beyond the baseline benefits provided by the federal system." [new york observer, 9/18/07 ]</p></span>



